untry for a decade. Individuals in the town of Makeni narrate survival through the rubric of love, and by telling their stories and bringing memory into the present, create for themselves a powerful basis on which to reaffirm the rightness of their choices and orient themselves to a livable everyday. The book illuminates a social world based on love, a deep, compassionate relationship based on material exchange and nurturing, that transcends romance and binds people together across space and through time. In situating their wartime lives firmly in this social world, they call into question the government’s own narrative that Makeni residents openly collaborated with the rebel RUF during its three-year occupation of the town. Residents argue instead that it was the government’s disloyalty to its people, rather than rebel invasion and occupation, which destroyed the town and forced uneasy co-existence between civilians and militants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWar and societyzSierra Leone. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  acivilians.  acultural memory.  aethnographies.  aevangelists.  afathers.  agovernment.  ahuman impact.  alife and death.  amakeni.  amilitants.  amilitary history.  amodern history.  anonfiction accounts.  aovercoming trauma.  apersonal stories.  apolitical.  apoliticians.  apower of love.  arebel forces.  arebels.  asierra leone.  asierra leoneans.  asocial justice.  asocial world.  asoldiers.  astudents.  asurvival.  atraders.  atraumatic experiences.  atrue stories.  aviolence.  awartime experiences.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027379540uh